th German (rarely <b>Kästl</b>): from a pet form of the Latin personal name <i>Castulus</i> ‘the chaste one’, an early Christian saint's name."],"variants":[{"name":"Kastler","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto.","German and Swiss German: status name for the steward of a castle, originally for one of the four officials in the king's service (from Latin <i>castellum</i>).","South German: variant of   Kastl   2."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde von Kastl was born about 1036, in Kastl, Altötting, Bavaria, Germany, her father, Graf Hermann I von Kastl, was -3 and her mother, Haziga von Dießen, was 10. She married Rapoto IV. von Cham before 1065. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1065, at the age of 30."},"et":{"about 1036–1065":"umbes 1036–1065","1036–1065":"1036–1065","1055–1103":"1055–1103","1056–1071":"1056–1071","1056–Female":"1056–Surnud","1034–1080":"1034–108